Congrats, You have all the tools you need to build your own chat client! Your goal in this project will be to create a chat application by using HTML, CSS, JS, and jQuery, and by making HTTP requests to a server in the background, via JavaScript. (You won't need to edit the server, that part is all handled for you.) You can see a working example version of the chat client at http://chatbuilder.hackreactor.com/?example=1.
We've provided 3 helper functions that can do most of the work for you at first, so you should start by figuring out how those work and building your client on top of them. Next, you'll be asked to delete those helpers and rebuild their functionality. By going in this order, you'll have a strong understanding of the project at a high level before you begin tackling the harder details. If you're new to developing for the web, you may find it useful to refer to the tutorials "Try jQuery" (http://try.jquery.com/) and "Explore and Master Chrome DevTools" (http://discover-devtools.codeschool.com/).
Ok, get started! You'll need to complete each of the following steps, probably in this order since each one builds on the previous.
1. Experiment with the Chat.display() helper 2. Experiment with the Chat.fetch() helper 3. Hook the two together 4. Set your app up to refresh the list of messages every 3 seconds. 5. Experiment with the Chat.send() helper 6. Allow the user to enter their own chat messages via the input box. 7. Woohoo, you're done with beginner phase--time to delete the helpers! 8. Add delete Chat.display; as the first line of your JS. 9. Add delete Chat.fetch; as the second line of your JS. 10. Add delete Chat.send; as the third line of your JS.
You can access more detailed explanations of each step by passing the step number into Chat.guide() . When you need help, please reach out to your interviewer rather than a friend--We're happy to help!

We have a project in the pipeline here at Hack Reactor that hasn't been started yet, and I'd love to accelerate it by letting students take the first crack at it. Here's the idea:
I've been thinking how cool it would be for people learning to program if they could actually see all the variables, values, scopes, and closures that get created as a javascript program runs. A tool could let them step through lines of code one-at-a-time, and quickly build a mental model of what the interpreter does with that code.
We take Narcissus, hook it up to a text box in a web page for entering code, run that code code in a debugging mode that goes line-by-line, and render the in-memory state using D3.
Employers really love projects that do nerdy things--just ask Nathan. They think people who write technical services and products are themselves hyper technical individuals, so I expect the accomplishment of having written this tool to be a pretty huge feather in your cap. We would use it like crazy as a teaching tool here, and I plan on featuring this project as a learning tool we provide to the world on our website as soon as it's production ready. This means we would keep working on it after you're done, making it gradually better and better, possibly working with future generations of students.
NOTE: This could also be a really huge undertaking, depending on how accessible the Narcissus runtime is, and how much you let the scope creep on your features. Getting to MVP before adding anything would be crucial in this case.
So let me know if you're interested in working on this problem--I'd love to make this tool a reality sooner than expected with your help!
